-- Contrapositive (Distinct from Contraposition)
--
-- Classical: To prove A -> B, prove ~B -> ~A instead
-- CredTT: ROBUST implication between stability regions
--         Different from contraposition which is about equivalence
--
-- Example: Prove "if n^2 even then n even"
-- by proving "if n odd then n^2 odd"
--
-- Classical: equivalent approaches
-- CredTT: different stability properties!

-- CONTRAPOSITIVE PROOF:
-- Instead of proving A -> B directly,
-- Prove ~B -> ~A and appeal to equivalence

-- But in CredTT, the equivalence is NOT exact!

-- Direct: A -> B @ c
postulate direct : A_implies_B [ c ]

-- Contrapositive: ~B -> ~A @ ?
-- NOT the same credence!

-- Why? Negation FLIPS stability:
-- If A -> B is Stable1, then ~B -> ~A might be Stable1 too
-- But the credence relationship is through negation

-- Direct proof:
-- A @ c_a, (A -> B) @ c_f
-- B @ c_a * c_f

-- Contrapositive use:
-- ~B @ c_nb, (~B -> ~A) @ c_cp
-- ~A @ c_nb * c_cp
-- A @ 1 - (c_nb * c_cp)  [if we want A from ~A]

-- The math is DIFFERENT!

-- Example: n odd -> n^2 odd @ 1 (definitely true)
-- Contrapositively: n^2 even -> n even @ 1

-- But if we had uncertainty:
-- n odd -> n^2 odd @ 0.9
-- What is n^2 even -> n even @ ?

-- Negation: c(~P) = 1 - c(P) = ~c(P)
-- ~(n odd) = n even, ~(n^2 odd) = n^2 even

-- Contrapositive credence:
-- (A -> B) @ c implies (~B -> ~A) @ f(c) for some f

-- In classical: f(c) = c (exact equivalence)
-- In CredTT: f involves negation of credences

-- The KEY insight:
-- Contrapositive is VALID but NOT free
-- The stability transformation matters
-- Direct proof and contrapositive proof are different PATHS
-- They arrive at related but not identical conclusions

-- Stable1 implication:
postulate stable_impl : A_implies_B [ 1 ]
stable stable_impl

-- Contrapositive is also stable (negation of stable endpoint)
-- But the path through negation changes the character
